What are Raisins?
Raisins are naturally dried grapes produced through sun drying or mechanical dehydration, with Thompson Seedless grapes serving as the primary variety used for commercial production in the United States. California accounts for nearly 100% of U.S. commercial raisin production, benefiting from ideal climatic conditions for grape cultivation and drying.

Raisins are valued for their rich nutritional profile, offering:

·         Dietary Fiber for digestive health

·         Natural Antioxidants that support overall wellness

·         Potassium and essential minerals

·         Natural sugars without artificial additives

·         Long shelf life through controlled moisture content (14–15%)

With growing consumer preference for healthy snacking, raisins have become widely used across breakfast cereals, bakery products, confectionery, snack mixes, dairy products, and food service applications. The industry has also embraced sustainable farming practices, with 82% of producers adopting water-efficient cultivation methods and organic raisins accounting for approximately 35% of total production.

